explanation:
OS_CHECK_POINTER: Macro/func used at the top of the function. It may perform logging, return, abort or other side-effects; understanding its expansion is required to know whether subsequent code can be skipped or is dead.
OS_printf: Appears in the static call graph (likely used by OS_CHECK_POINTER or error reporting). Needed to determine whether logging calls are executed and whether they produce side effects that make code non-dead.
UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr: These unit-test/stub helpers appear in the static call graph (likely referenced by macros used in this build). Include them to understand any test-harness-induced side-effects or early-returns that affect reachability/necessity of code.
memset: Standard library call used to zero filesys_info. Required to determine whether this initialization is meaningful (initialization vs assignment) for the dead-code decision.
OS_MAX_NUM_OPEN_FILES, OS_MAX_FILE_SYSTEMS: Constants assigned into filesys_info fields. Their values and usage elsewhere affect whether those assignments are redundant (i.e., dead) or required.
OS_object_iter_t: Iterator type for iterating object ids. Needed to understand iterator state storage, lifetime and whether iterator operations have side-effects beyond counting.
OS_FileSysFilterFree: Filter function passed to the iterator. Its behavior determines which objects are counted by the iterator; needed to know whether the loop bodies ever execute and thus whether the increments are meaningful.
OS_ObjectIdIteratorInit: Initializes the iterator; semantics (e.g., side-effects, error/return behavior) determine whether the loop executes or is skipped and whether init has effects that cannot be removed.
OS_ObjectIdIteratorGetNext: Drives each while loop. Crucial to know its return behavior and side-effects to determine if the loop body (++FreeFds/++FreeVolumes) is executed and thus non-dead.
OS_ObjectIdIteratorDestroy: Cleans up the iterator; may have side-effects that make it required (non-dead). Also needed to determine correctness of removing the loop.
OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_STREAM, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_FILESYS: Object type constants passed to the iterator; they affect which objects are enumerated and therefore whether the counting loops are meaningful.
OS_SUCCESS: Function return value constant; verify whether returning this value is required or could be optimized away.

These symbols together provide the control-flow, side-effect and semantic context needed to decide whether any operations in OS_GetFsInfo (assignments, memset, iterator loops, init/destroy) are actually required for program behaviour or constitute dead code.
